segments.text: Welcome to Rising We Have a Great Friday Show for you today. I'm Jason Nichols. I'm joined
at the desk today by the Washington spectators. Amber Aethi. Did I get it right? Aethi? You
did. All right. Go ahead. I'm glad that I didn't say Aethi. Amber, great to be with
you this morning and it's great to be with all of you. Filling in for Robbie and
Brie today, we tied him up. We put him in the basement and we are here today for
you. I know you love it. Amber, what's going on? Hey, we've got lots to get into.
Up first, President Biden is expected to announce his re-election campaign next
week. According to new reporting from the Washington Post, the president and his
team are eyeing this upcoming Tuesday, the four year anniversary of Biden's 2020
campaign launch as the big day. Meanwhile, on the other side of the aisle,
new Wall Street Journal role polling released today finds former President
Donald Trump tops the GOP primary field, even as he faces prosecution in New
York. Support for Florida Governor Ron DeSantis, who previously enjoyed a narrow
lead over Trump in the journals December poll dropped 14 points amongst likely
GOP primary voters. He now trails 13 points behind the former president. So
what do you make of this? You know, you're the resident conservative. What do you
make of this? Yeah, it's interesting. I mean, I first, it seemed like Floridians in
particular were really disturbed by President Trump's attacks on Florida
Governor Ron DeSantis when he went after him ahead of the midterm elections and
after his campaign announcement and tried to flip the script on COVID. But since then,
it doesn't seem like DeSantis has gained any momentum whatsoever. And maybe his strategy of
kind of sitting back and not responding to Trump has not served him very well. Yeah, I think you
have to be a fighter. People are looking for a fighter. And Donald Trump, one of the things that
he does really well, even with his issues on COVID and the vaccines and all of that,
even when he was criticized by his own base, he stands up to them. He's like, you know, I'm the
boss here. And I think people like that. People embrace that. Ron DeSantis comes across us,
like I've said this several times, he comes across small. He comes, he's not the biggest guy in the
room. You don't look at Ron DeSantis and say, he's our leader. And I think that's why you're
seeing a lot of Florida Republicans, Rutherford, Stu, Stu, Stu, Stu, Stu, Stu, Stu, Stu,
Byron Donalds, yeah. Byron Donalds, Mass, all these guys who are Florida Republicans. And you know,
they were trying to, the DeSantis camp was trying to keep them from endorsing Trump. And they've gone
with Trump. And I think it's because Trump has that CEO feel and he's an entertainer. And that's
something that you can't, that's in your spinal cord. Yeah, you can't teach that Trump is actually
very funny. And DeSantis, I don't think has that same charisma. He's obviously very intelligent.
He's very tapped into his policy decisions. He keeps a very small circle, which is one of the
things I always criticized Trump for was he was horrible at picking personnel and surrounding
himself with the right people. But the things that I'm hearing from conservatives is that when they
watch DeSantis try to work like a handshake line, it's just awkward. He doesn't relate to people
very well. He's naturally an introvert. And Trump is the exact opposite. He's really good at
connecting with people one on one. Yeah, and all of our presidents in recent memory, you go back to
George W. Bush, he was not a good speaker. But one of the things anybody I know who's met George
W. Bush says, you connect with the guy one on one. Barack Obama is a generational kind of talent
in politics. And then even Joe Biden, even with his sniffing the hair and all of that kind of stuff,
you shake his hand and he connects with people. And I think that DeSantis just doesn't have it,
whatever it is. And I think a lot of Republicans are starting to realize that he's not the guy.
And I think maybe he'll have a chance in 2028. That's a possibility. He could be a strong candidate,
especially if he's going up against someone like Kamala Harris. I think that's true. These are two
people who just are not necessarily good interviewers. We saw DeSantis flub,
the whole Ukraine issue, which I think a lot of Republicans saw him as kind of waffling and going
on both sides of the fence. So he's kind of, he seems like he's just kind of looking for a lane.
He doesn't know where to go. He doesn't want to offend people. And that's the exact opposite
of Donald Trump who projects strength. I think against the Kamala Harris, he could do well.
But I'm not convinced Kamala Harris is going to be the nominee in 2028, whether Joe Biden wins or
loses. So I think he's got a chance down the road. But as you stated, there are certain things you
can't teach in politics. And I don't think Ron DeSantis has it. He was lucky to win that Florida race.
The first time against Andrew Gillum. Andrew Gillum, I think, for all his issues is an
incredibly talented politician. And he was lucky to win that race because we started to see some of
those scandals start to bubble to the surface. DeSantis is not one of those talented guys. And
he's latched on to the right culture war policies that were popular with Republicans. But they're
starting to actually see him and Trump is Trump is the man right now. The other thing that I'm hearing
is that in regards to a potential DeSantis campaign is that because of how much of a
micro manager he is and how involved he is in every single decision, it's really hard to
to grow that type of operation on a national level. I mean, what is he going to be doing?
Hopping into every campaign briefing call and asking about exactly how many doors are being
knocked in this precinct in Iowa, it's just not feasible to run a national campaign. That way,
you have to be willing to offload responsibility to other people. So something that works really
well in the governor's office might not work so well when you're trying to run for president.
But I wanted to ask you about Biden's ambitions because he's set to announce his reelection campaign.
And as bad as I think Biden is and as as low as his polling is, I don't see any other Democrat
that could take that that the reins right now. No, I think Biden number one, he's an incumbent.
And I think it would be a big mistake for anybody to go against an incumbent president because it
makes it seem like your base doesn't have it figured out. You picked the wrong guy. So I've been
saying, I know a lot of people and their problems within mainstream Democratic politics, their
problem with Biden isn't really his policies. It's his age. That's the big issue. So we look at what
Biden has done. And I know that conservatives and many other people are upset with Biden for many
things. But when you look at what he's done, he said he was going to be this uniter, right?
But we've seen some bipartisan legislation under Biden. So they may not like him, but we got
bipartisan infrastructure. We got the Respect for Marriage Act. We got the bipartisan Safer
Communities Act, which, you know, we got the first major gun legislation in 30 years.
That was broadly popular. I think that Joe Biden actually has a lot to run on. He's been
hampered by inflation and by some of the things in the financial sector. But when you look at
even his base, which is people like African American voters who are upset, I think, about the lack
of action on voting rights and a few other things, he still can tell some of the economic gains
that have happened in the fourth quarter of 2022. We saw that African Americans gained the most
in terms of wage increases. So I think he has stuff to run on. We're going to see how this all works out.
And we'll be back with more rising after this.
The U.K. has agreed as a green light to become a member of NATO. This, according to NATO Secretary
Jan Stoltenberg, who said this week that all the countries in the transatlantic military
alliance have agreed to admit the war-torn country to the club after the war with Russia is over.
Here's Stoltenberg speaking with reporters during his first visit to Ukraine since the start of the
invasion. Let's take a look. All NATO allies have agreed that Ukraine will become a NATO member.
But the main focus now is, of course, on how to ensure that Ukraine prevails.
However, German Defense Minister Boris Pistorius said Thursday that the door is open for Ukraine
to join. But quote, this is not the time to decide. Here to discuss more on this is
Lieutenant Colonel Daniel Davis. Thank you so much for joining us, Colonel.
Always my pleasure. Thanks for having me. So is this the right time? It seems like there's a bit of a
discussion happening among world leaders as to whether or not this could potentially inflame
tensions between the Ukrainian and Russian war. You know, I don't know what Stoltenberg's
intent is or what the senior leaders of NATO think is going to be accomplished by making
statements like this. I don't know if they think it's going to deter somehow Russia when it hasn't
done it for the last 14 years. But this is almost certainly going to have the exact opposite impact.
If anything, this will cause Russia to just even more sternly decide that no negotiations are
useful and that they need to double down on trying to win their war militarily.
Because look, we got to understand that NATO advancement in Ukraine up to the Russian border
was one of the major sparks for the war in the first place and to talk about that last year.
So I don't think this is a good idea. And interestingly enough, about an hour ago,
Viktor Orban of Hungary, a NATO member, when told that all NATO members agreed that Ukraine would
become a member of NATO, he said, what? No, I don't think that's the case. So I'm not sure
that there's the unity that Stoltenberg is saying there is.
So I have a question and that's about Finland and Finland joining NATO. Do you think that that's
made a difference for Russia? Are they upset about Finland joining and has that escalated things?
Has that played any role in any of this? Well, it certainly has been bad from the Russian
perspective. I don't think that Putin ever thought that Finland and Sweden would join NATO.
So it's definitely a negative from Russia's perspective and something they miscalculated on.
But I don't think that it's going to play too much of a military role because when you look at the
literally the military geography of that part of the country, that poses a lot less of a
threat and a risk of ground invasion into the Russian territory as the territory in
Ukraine would if Ukraine became a NATO member there, which is why they've said that Ukraine
is their non-negotiable red line that they won't allow without continuing to fight the war.
I was seeing some chatter on social media from people who were convinced that this was Stoltenberg
trying to embroil all of these NATO countries into a world war. Do you take that cynical of a
view on it or do you think maybe he was just trying to create this unification where it didn't quite
exist? I don't think that Stoltenberg or anybody in NATO desires a war with Russia because they
know that it would be catastrophic for us and almost certainly lead to nuclear escalation.
So I don't think they desire that, but I think there's a bigger problem or at least a
compounding problem that I think they believe that by saying these kinds of statements that
they can project power, that they can cause hesitation and Moscow. But I mean those efforts have fallen
so flat for the last couple of years in particular and throughout this war, I just don't know why
to continue doing things that have demonstrated they're not going to work.
Well, so I have a two-part question. Number one, does Ukraine right now meet the requirements to
join NATO in terms of democracy and protection of minorities? We had heard that they were decades
away before the war. Are they any closer? No, they're not. And it's 100% certain that that's not the
case that they're any closer now. As a matter of fact, the reason why Viktor Orban is against
even talking about extended NATO membership to Ukraine is because of the minorities, the
Hungarian minorities in the western part of Ukraine, which are being in his view,
they're being abused and they're not having their rights and they're having a lot of their
rights taken away. Many of them are being what he says is being pressed, gamed into military
service to go fight when they don't want to. So there's a lot of problems with that, but just
across the board, I mean by NATO's own founding documents, Ukraine is nowhere near
liable to join the alliance or qualify. In any case, there's no way that they do.
So, Lieutenant Colonel, I have one final question and that is about, does this, you know, what Stoltenberg
said, does this actually empower the Russian propaganda arm and their justification for the
war? You know, they've been saying things about NATO and NATO has been a big enemy within
the Russian populace. And people were saying that perhaps the war was getting unpopular.
Do you think Stoltenberg saying that Ukraine is going to join NATO actually empowers Vladimir
Putin with his own people? I don't think that Russia, you know,
thinks that the war is going well or that they're against it or whatever. I think most of them
are resigned to it, especially if you look at the polls, but this absolutely plays into the theme
that the Russian government has been using since the outset that this is not a war between Russia
and Ukraine. This is a war between NATO and Russia using Ukraine as a weapon against them. And
certainly there's lots of physical evidence to support that view from the Russian perspective in
that their economy, we're attempting to destroy it with all these sanctions. We're giving all these
weapons targeting information to their enemy ammunition, everything to kill Russian soldiers.
So I mean, from their perspective, it very much is a proxy war and that it's NATO against them.
And this just helps, I think, fuel that.
According to a Washington Post report, the leak of Pentagon classified documents that detail the
fight in Ukraine revealed that the United States warned Zelensky that he would not be able to hold
on to the city of Bakhmud. But despite the warnings, the grim and grim assessment,
Ukrainian forces have managed to keep a hold of this key stronghold. What do you make of this intel?
Look, that was the right call. I was saying that I think as far back as December that the
reasonable prudent thing for Ukraine was to evacuate from Bakhmud and reset up on
unexisting already prepared defensive lines a little bit further to the west from where they
could extract a much higher cost on Russia. But the reason why they have held on this far
is because they have continued Ukraine has to throw many of their reserves and many of the
forces that they had trained for an offensive in the spring or the summer. The intent was
for Ukraine to launch an offensive to hit Russia. But by holding on to Bakhmud when it was
militarily untenable, they have basically delayed the process, but they have sacrificed up to tens
of thousands of troops that they needed for an offensive, which now puts the offensive,
either making it have to delay further or making it have a smaller chance of success. So I think
that this is going to come back to Biden. Well, thank you so much, Lieutenant. We really appreciate
your perspective on this very important issue. More rising after this.
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Dick Durbin is asking Supreme Court Chief Justice John Roberts
to testify before Congress. According to The Hill, Roberts is facing pressure from Democratic
lawmakers to investigate details surrounding the undisclosed transactions and free trips
Justice Clarence Thomas has taken, which were reportedly paid for by Republican billionaire and
donor Harlan Crow. Democrats on the Judiciary panel have expressed support for a quote binding
code of ethics for scodist justices, which according to The Hill, Roberts did not welcome back in 2011.
In a letter to Roberts, Durbin wrote, there has been a steady stream of revelations regarding
justices falling short of the ethical standards expected of other federal judges and indeed of
public servants generally. These problems were already apparent back in 2011. And the court's
decade-long failure to address them has contributed to a crisis of public confidence. The status
quo was no longer tenable. The time has come for a new public conversation on ways to restore
confidence in the court's ethical standards. I invite you to join in political reports.
Durbin said Roberts' testimony on ethics issues would improve public faith in the High Court.
Senator Lindsey Graham weighed in on the matter saying, I would support his decision not to come
if that's what he wanted to do, The Hill reports. So what do you make of this? Should he come
and testify or not? I just feel like this is all big to do about really nothing. The, I mean,
the ethics standards have only changed very recently. So a lot of these so-called free trips and
things that were happening before friends were not things that he would have necessarily been
required to report in the past. And it's pretty common amongst go to justices to have friends
in high places. I mean, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, if you were looking at some of the travel that she
went on with friends, we didn't really have the same reaction to that when she was alive.
Because these people obviously don't get paid. They're not able to have the same level of
income that perhaps politicians have or are able to make after they leave Congress.
So they end up becoming friends with these people who are able to sort of treat them in these ways.
Now, obviously, there's always going to be the question of whether or not this is influencing
their ability to be judicious, judiciously impartial. But that would be a question we would
have to ask of every justice on the bench, not just Clarence Thomas. No, absolutely. I agree with
you on one point. That is that the ethical standards have just kind of been written
when it comes to the gifts. And I think most people on the left don't think the gifts were
the biggest problem. It's not about what happened in terms of him taking him on vacation and things
like that. It was the financial transaction that occurred over the land where he got paid, the real
estate. That, of course, dates back to the Nixon era when you had Abe Fortis who got $20,000
from a guy named Wolfson who was a guy on Wall Street. I know it's kind of funny Wolfson Wall
Street. But he got that money. He actually gave the $20,000 back. But he was still forced off the
court. And when we look at what other federal judges have had to deal with in terms of their ethics,
Clarence Thomas not disclosing that is an actual issue. I was with the whole thing about him going
on a trip with his friends and even using the private jet. You're allowed to have friends. You're
allowed to travel with your friends. If your friend wants to pick up the bill, pick up the tab,
that's one thing. It's different when you don't disclose a financial transaction. In addition to
that, Harlan Crow has had some business before the court, not directly. But he certainly funds
organizations that actually do have business before the court and actually have done business
before the court. So could there be some influence peddling? I will say that Clarence Thomas has
always been Clarence Thomas in terms of his politics at least since he was in law school.
It's not that I think that Clarence Thomas, this may have changed some of his views. I don't think
he was a liberal justice and then got some money. And then Harlan Crow took him on a trip and he
was like, all right then. And then I always said change. But that is, in my view, an ethical violation
based on what we kicked other justices out for in the past and the fact that he should have
disclosed a financial transaction, he says he lost money on it. But it doesn't matter. You still have
to. Yeah, I mean, so he's amended his form. And this is not uncommon again for scotish justices
to amend their filings. Katanji Brown Jackson has had to do it. Ruth Bader Ginsburg has had to do
it. She didn't report the sale of a stock, for example. So I mean, this is, I just don't think
it's as big of a deal as it's being made out to be based on the historical precedent for it.
And even public public, public, which first reported on this lack of disclosure, didn't even
write a follow up piece about the amendment or claims like they some major victory against Clarence
Thomas. So I don't even think that they are propping it up as this major ethical violation
that it's been made out to be in the rest of the press. Again, I think it's all about
the rules. First of all, we need to iron out more rules. And that's why I think
Chief Justice John Roberts needs to go before Dick Durbin in the Senate and talk about
the rules and the ethical rules for the court. Because I think it's not right that you have
someone who has a lifetime position for the right who always talks about. And people like Lindsey
Graham, who talk about the three letter organizations and the bureaucracy and the unelected bureaucracy.
You have basically people who are unelected who have a lifetime position. And they're kind of
given free rein to do what they want. And I think that that's really problematic. They need to iron
these rules out a little more. And Chief Justice Roberts needs to go before the Senate and talk
about what the rules actually are for the Senate, excuse me, for the scotest justices. But I think
we can see that this is a violation. And again, based on historical precedent,
based on the fact that Abe Fortis was forced off the court for $20,000. Again, $20,000 in the
early 70s was a lot more money. But he actually gave the money back, but he was forced out by the
president pressured him. Other justices on the court pressured him to vacate his seat on the court.
And we see that if this happened to one of the lower federal courts, that person would have been
had a serious reprimand or even had to leave the court. And I think that to let
just the really powerful judges, the nine of them get away with things that we would punish
some other federal judge around the country for, I think sets of really bad precedent.
And it's against what a lot of conservatives are saying about these, you know, the three
letter organizations, the unelected bureaucracy. I'm all about rules being applied equally. I would
say here's the deal that I would want to make. If Chief Justice John Roberts is going to come
testify about the new ethics rules, then I also want an update on the investigation into this
leaker of the DAWS decision because what's going on with that? We still don't know who that person
is. I mean, there's only so many likely suspects, right? So let's do both at the same time.
Let's kill two birds with one stone. No, I hear that. But also we have to remember that Alito
was talking about that at his private dinners and talking about what he was going to do in terms of
DAWS and abortion altogether. So the leaker could be Alito. It could be Alito.
Which is really kind of... Well, that would be fun. I don't know. Let's do it.
I mean, all of them need to be held accountable. And I'm not just saying that about the conservative
justices. You know, I'm talking about if Katarji Brown Jackson does this or Elena Kagan or Sotomayor,
if they are, you know, sitting there and getting money and... For sure. Everybody has to disclose.
I think we're in agreement on that. All right. Great discussion. We're rising after this.
Capitol Hill is up in arms over the debt ceiling fight. According to new reporting from The Hill,
both conservatives and moderates are less than pleased about the newly unveiled debt limit bill,
leaving party leaders scrambling to shore up votes.
Here to break it down for us is The Hill's own congressional reporter, Michael Chanel.
Good to be with you, Mikey. Can you break it down for us? Thanks, guys, for having me.
Yeah. So essentially what we've been talking about this debt limit, right, for the past three
months trying to figure out what's going to happen, how could Democrats and Republicans get on the
same page. And for those three months, we've been at a stalemate. We've been at a standstill.
Both sides are digging in their heels. But we saw some movement this week. House Republicans
introduced their debt limit bill. It's their proposal of what to do with the debt limit as we're
creeping up on that summer deadline. And essentially what this would do is it would raise the debt
limit by $1.5 trillion or until March, the end of March of next year, whichever comes first.
And then it also is paired with what Republicans are saying amounts to $4.5 trillion in spending
cuts. Of course, this has been something that House Republicans, specifically conservatives,
were pushing for during the speaker's race back in January. And so now those concessions
that Speaker McCarthy made, they're coming to term and we're seeing those spending cut proposals.
So House Republican leadership is hoping to bring this bill to the floor next week
to pass it and then send it to the Senate, where it really has no chance of moving,
obviously Senate controlled by Democrats. But the only thing is, it's not an easy path to 218
votes in the House right now, despite the fact that this was a bill crafted by House Republicans.
As mentioned, as you guys mentioned, moderates and conservatives both have some misgivings about
this bill. Some are saying that they're leaning no. We've even heard a few say there are hard
nose, there are still negotiations happening behind the scenes to potentially change the
text of the bill to bring more House Republicans on board. But the reason why this is crucial
is because House Republicans are working with a very slight majority, right? They can only
afford to lose four votes, assuming that all Democrats vote against it, which Hakim Jeffery
suggested just this week that that's going to be the case. So again, House Republicans are hoping
to bring this to the floor next week. It is not a sure thing that it has the votes. There's going
to be a lot of wrangling and negotiating happening behind the scenes in the coming days.
Well, meanwhile, President Joe Biden has said that he's only interested in a clean bill to raise
the debt ceiling. So even if they are able to hammer out some of these differences within the
Republican caucus, what are the chances that anything that goes to the president's desk is
going to be signed? Yeah, so that's another part. The short answer is there's no chance, right? But
just to back it up even a little more, when we're talking about this Republican bill,
it's not even going to get past the Senate. Again, it would be subject to the 60-vote
threshold. That would mean that at least 10 Republicans would have to be on board. There's
no appetite. I mean, there's no, that would mean that at least 10 Democrats, I'm sorry,
would have to come on board. There's no appetite there in the Senate. So really,
what this bill is being seen as is the opening salvo in what are going to be these really high
stakes negotiations for the debt limit. This is House Republicans' way of saying,
this is what we want to see in a debt limit and spending cut proposal. This is what House
Republicans would put our way behind. But obviously, the White House is not going to get on board with
this. So this is sort of the opening flagpole in the negotiations, and we'll see where we can go
from there. The only thing is, is President Biden and Democrats have been adamant that they want a
clean debt ceiling increase. They do not want to see spending cuts. Again, both sides are really
digging in their heels. There's no indication of what the answer to this issue will be, which I will
say has to come soon because analysts and experts have been saying that the debt limit,
we will hit the debt limit over the summer. Goldman Sachs came out this week and said that
based on tax returns that came in, it looks like we could hit the debt limit early June,
which is very early. It's compared to the August, July timeline we were talking about.
So lawmakers are going to have to start moving because there's been a warning that
the economic effects of a default, which obviously the U.S. has never experienced,
could be cataclysmic. So there's going to have to be some movement here.
House Republicans are trying to inch that along, but again, both sides are digging in their heels.
So where we go from here remains to be seen. So is there a sense that on the
from far right Republicans that they think that these negotiations or what Kevin McCarthy is
proposing doesn't go far enough? Is that what it is? And moderates want perhaps a little less?
Is that where the disagreement lies? Sort of. Yeah, that's essentially
broadly speaking what the issue is. So there are some conservative Republicans,
Matt Gaetz, Chip Roy. They want stricter work requirements for some of these entitlement
programs for things like food stamps and things like Medicaid, Social Security and Medicare,
though, are not being touched. They're not included in this bill. So some of those conservative
Republicans want the work requirements to be beefed up. But then you have someone like
Congresswoman Nancy Mase, who is known to be a moderate within the conference. She's concerned
about some energy provisions that are being repealed from the inflation reduction act that
House Democrats passed last summer. She said that something like solar energy is really important
in her district in South Carolina. So she's voicing some concerns about that. So to get to your point,
yes, a lot of the general confines of it is that conservatives want more, moderates want less.
But there's one more angle to this is the fact that this bill is 320 pages long.
It was just released this week. There are a ton of provisions in it. It's not just that
debt ceiling increase. It's also all of the spending cuts. It's other provisions. I mean,
HR one, that massive energy package that House Republicans just recently passed,
the entire HR one is in this bill. So we're talking about a massive piece of legislation here.
A ton of lawmakers are still sifting through the details, trying to figure out where they stand
on it. But in terms of the ones who have some misgivings, I spoke to some conservative Republicans
this week, they're happy with how negotiations are going. They said that Republican leadership
is being receptive to some of their requests. So that's some good optimism that we don't always
see on Capitol Hill. But again, in terms of where this goes, they are not at 218 votes yet.
So there's going to definitely be more discussions.
Meanwhile, here's what White House press secretary,
Korean Jean Pierre, had to say on the matter.
The way to have a real negotiation on the budget is for House Republicans to take threats of default.
When it comes to the economy and what it could potentially do the economy off the table, House
Republicans need to get to work and stop the delay and put a bill on the floor that's going to avoid
the fault. So it looks like Republicans have now offered something. And then the other question I
had as a follow up to Korean Jean Pierre's statement was that last week Speaker McCarthy
said that he actually hadn't heard from President Biden. Has that changed?
Right. So the last time President Biden and McCarthy met on this issue,
specifically a meeting on the debt limit, was back on February 1st.
President Biden has said that he is not going to have another conversation about the debt limit
until House Republicans released their annual budget, which they have not done. It was
meant to come out previously, but it's been delayed. They've sort of been kicking that can
down the road. So yeah, President Biden, Speaker McCrudden, they've met on different matters.
They took part in a St. Patty's Day event together on Capitol Hill.
But in terms of meeting specifically on the debt limit, no, they have not.
And just recently this week, there was a phone conversation between President Biden,
Chuck Schumer and Akim Jeffries. And there was a readout from the White House afterwards,
and they called on House Republicans to, let's deal with the debt limit, let's pass a clean
debt limit increase. And then we can talk about budget negotiations later, because again,
that's going to be a thing as we move into the fall when we are closer to the end of the fiscal
year. So yeah, I mean, again, this just gets back to the main idea that both sides
are being very, they're being very adamant about their positions. We're entering into a massive
game of chicken that has serious implications for the economy. But again, over House Republicans
are trying to move it a little forward, but we'll see if they have the votes to do that.
All right. Well, we'll definitely have to hear more about this, Mikey. Thank you for coming on,
and we'll be back with more rising.
This Supreme Court is expected to decide by tonight whether a commonly used abortion pill
should continue to be accessible. The Biden administration had requested an emergency stay
to keep the Food and Drug Administration's approval of the pill, Miffa Pristone, in place.
A lower court banned it, but just as Samuel Alito put the brakes on that court's ruling.
Meanwhile, Donald Trump's campaign made it clear the former president does not support
a national abortion ban. The former president and 2024 GOP presidential candidate believes
